HEADWORD: Dominate
<hw>Dom"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Dominated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dominating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>dominatus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>dominari</ets> to dominate, fr. <ets>dominus</ets> master,
lord. See <er>Dame</er>, and cf. <er>Domineer</er>.]</ety> <def>To
predominate over; to rule; to govern.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A city
<xex>dominated</xex> by the ax.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We everywhere meet with Slavonian nations either dominant or
<qex>dominated</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Tooke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dominate</ent>⟦br⟧

